The developer has made a change to the JavaEnvUtils class in the Apache Ant build tool. Specifically, they have replaced two lines of code with a new block of code that uses the DeweyDecimal class from the Apache Commons Math library to parse and manipulate the version number of Java.

The original code was:
```
javaVersionNumber = Integer.parseInt(v) * 10;
javaVersion = v;
```

The new code is:
```
DeweyDecimal pv = new DeweyDecimal(v);
javaVersionNumber = pv.get(0) * 10;
if (pv.getSize() > 1) {
    javaVersionNumber += pv.get(1);
}
javaVersion = pv.toString();
```

This change allows for more accurate handling of Java version numbers that include decimal points, such as "1.8.0_202". The DeweyDecimal class is used to parse the version number into its individual components and then recombine them into a single integer value for comparison purposes, and also to convert it back into a string representation for display or

